<TITLE>Since You Asked: State 'kicker' tied to revenue predictions, not revenue</TITLE>


<TEXT>
OK, so what <EVENT eid="e1" class="I_STATE">say</EVENT> you Wise Ones over there: Since Oregon has <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">gotten</EVENT> more than $60 million in revenue from taxes on pot sales do you see in our future an Oregon kicker check <EVENT eid="e3" class="OCCURRENCE">coming</EVENT> to us? 
 
 MadMax, by email 
 
We don't <EVENT eid="e4" class="I_STATE">want</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e5" class="OCCURRENCE">make</EVENT> you any madder, Max, but the kicker is not <EVENT eid="e6" class="STATE">tied</EVENT> to increased revenue, it is tied to what the forecast is for that revenue. 
 
For anyone who may be entirely unfamiliar with the kicker, it is a refund the state of Oregon provides to taxpayers when revenues come in higher than <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">expected</EVENT>. 
 
How it works is pretty simple to <EVENT eid="e8" class="OCCURRENCE">explain</EVENT>: The kicker is <EVENT eid="e9" class="OCCURRENCE">triggered</EVENT> when Oregon's tax revenues (minus corporate income taxes) <EVENT eid="e10" class="OCCURRENCE">exceed</EVENT> the forecast made at the <EVENT eid="e11" class="ASPECTUAL">start</EVENT> of the <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DURATION" value="P2Y">two-year</TIMEX3> budget cycle by 2 percent or more. When that <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">happens</EVENT>, all the revenue above the forecast must be <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">returned</EVENT> to taxpayers. There's also a corporate kicker, but the surplus generated by that kicker <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3> goes to schools. 
 
If the revenue comes in at 1.99999 percent higher than <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">predicted</EVENT>, the state gets to <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">keep</EVENT> it. But if it <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">hits</EVENT> 2 percent, the entire amount is <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">refunded</EVENT>. Taxpayers <EVENT eid="e18" class="I_STATE">get</EVENT> a refund equal to the amount exceeding the forecast, so if it's 3 percent over, individual taxpayers would <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">get</EVENT> 3 percent off their next tax bill. The state formerly <EVENT eid="e20" class="OCCURRENCE">sent</EVENT> out rebate checks but <EVENT eid="e21" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> it was more efficient and less expensive to <EVENT eid="e22" class="OCCURRENCE">connect</EVENT> the payments to the next tax bill rather than <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">sending</EVENT> out checks by the hundreds of thousands. 
 
But again, Max, the rebates <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">occur</EVENT> only when revenues <EVENT eid="e25" class="OCCURRENCE">exceed</EVENT> the state economists' <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">prediction</EVENT> by at least 2 percent. So if the economists <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">predicted</EVENT> a 20 percent <EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">increase</EVENT> in revenues  not likely, by the way  and it <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">came</EVENT> in under 22 percent, the state would <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">get</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">keep</EVENT> it. 
 
The reported $60.2 million in marijuana taxes could <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">impact</EVENT> the likelihood of the kicker kicking. The refund <EVENT eid="e33" class="OCCURRENCE">announced</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="2015">2015</TIMEX3> <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">amounted</EVENT> to $402 million, which <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">represented</EVENT> 3 percent more than what economists <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">predicted</EVENT>. 
 
Critics of the kicker <EVENT eid="e37" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> that it is a faulty process, as circumstances can greatly <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">change</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DURATION" value="P2Y">the two years</TIMEX3> of the biennium, <EVENT eid="e39" class="OCCURRENCE">making</EVENT> those predictions a bit of a crapshoot. Kicker supporters <EVENT eid="e40" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> it is a <EVENT eid="e41" class="OCCURRENCE">way</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e42" class="ASPECTUAL">keep</EVENT> state government from <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">growing</EVENT> too fast and to <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">keep</EVENT> more money in private hands. 
 
If there is a kicker attached to the <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">current</TIMEX3> biennium, it would be <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">announced</EVENT> following the end of the biennium, which is <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DATE" value="2017-07-31">July 31</TIMEX3>. The announcement usually occurs in <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DATE" value="2017-08">August</TIMEX3>. 
 
